Ford Go Bike System Data Analysis¶

By Marzuk Sulemana¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The data contains 183412 rows and 16 columns. Some of the columns in this data include duration_sec, start_station_id, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, member_birth_year etc.

Cleaning Data¶

Define:¶

  1. Drop all rows with null values.
  2. Correct all erroneous datatypes.
  3. Create column for duration in minutes.
  4. Drop all columns not needed in the analysis.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data contains 183412 rows and 16 columns. Some of the columns in this data include duration_sec, start_station_id, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, member_birth_year etc.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am more interested in how trip duration is dependent on other features of the data.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My expectations are that trip duration should depend on features such birth year, user type, gender, start station and end station.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Duration of rides seem to be dependent on age of users. And most of the duration are below 200 minutes. Some rides duration are as high as 1406 minutes, this may be as a result of riders forgetting to log off after using the bike.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The number of male users is higher than female users in both subscribers and customers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I have observed that regardless of the gender, users who are 60 years have less than 350 minutes bike durations. Also the least number of points shown by other gengers confirms that they are the least number of users in the system.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I was surprised to have observed that two female users with ages of 56 an 57 years have more than 1200 minutes bike duration. This maybe as result of not logging off after finnishing their ride.

Conclusions¶

From the explorations of the data, we have seen that bike duration is dependent on age where increase in user age leads to decrease in bike duration. We have also observed that even though there are more subscribers than customers in the system, Users who are customers turn to have longer bike duration than subscribers. Therfore, we might say that when users subscribe to the bikeshare system, it does not mean that they will have longer duration.
